.definition: in the course of time; eventually
.example: in time they came to accept the harsh reality

.definition: to develop in a particular way, or to have a particular result
.example: How will the game turn out?

.definition: to find a solution
.example: I’m trying to work out what it stands for.

.definition: to escape; to exit, to avoid doing something
.example: We need to get out of the house before the storm hits.

.definition: to be expected or required to do/be something according to a rule, a custom, an arrangement, etc.
.example: I didn’t go, but I was supposed to.

.definition: If you say that something is the case , you mean that it is true or correct
.example: It’s not the case that I don’t love him.

.definition: At the time when something happens that is after another event or situation has already passed or occurred
.example: By the time they arrive, he will have already left.

.definition: in addition to someone or something else
.example: Along with his dog, the cat slowly stopped eating.

.definition: generally speaking
.example: The population as a whole is getting healthier.

.definition: ready to; on the verge of
.example: I’m glad you’re finally home. I was just about to have dinner without you.

.definition: in the beginning
.example: Not at first, but just the other day there was one.

.definition: to continue doing something
.example: He could simply not carry on.

.definition: hurry, do something now (always used as a command)
.example: Come on, think about it!

.definition: (of an idea) to enter your mind
.example: We came to see it for what it was.

.definition: very often; repeatedly
.example: I wish you'd stop criticizing me all the time.

.definition: to give attention, effort, etc. to one particular subject, situation, or person rather than another
.example: But today I’d like to focus on something different.

.definition: something like this
.example: Economic growth makes us all richer, provides jobs, and so on.

.definition: to get out of bed
.example: I always get up at 7 A.M.

.definition: to stop doing or to stop trying to do something
.example: The problem was difficult, but Tom would not give up.

.definition: used when you are trying to explain or describe something, but you cannot be exact
.example: It was kind of strange to see him again.

.definition: to be responsible for or to take care of somebody/something
.example: If your child got a sickness, you wouldn't just let them down. Look after them.

.definition: as the end result of a succession or process
.example: At last we met over coffee last week.

.definition: one more time; another time
.example: Once again, this was completely unforeseen.

.definition: a little more or less than; a little before or after
.example: 20 or so people were at the party

.definition: to begin to deal with a job or responsibility
.example: I can now take on new responsibilities at work.

.definition: throughout; everywhere
.example: Oh no! I got ketchup all over my white sweater.

.definition: to start an activity with a particular aim
.example: She accomplished what she set out to do.

.definition: If you say that something may well happen, you mean that it is likely to happen
.example: He hasn’t yet but may well try before long.

.definition: You use followed by to say what comes after something else in a list or ordered set of things.
.example: The workshop will be followed by time for questions.

.definition: because
.example: It’s great in the sense that there are so many restaurants.

.definition: occupy time, space, or attention
.example: I don't want to take up any more of your time

.definition: to explain the reason for something or the cause of something
.example: They’ll need to account for their actions.

.definition: with reference to; as for; regarding
.example: What are you thinking, as far as feasibility on this?

.definition: having to do with, about, relating to
.example: They spoke on issues concerned with culture.

.definition: apart from; except.
.example: He claims not to own anything other than his home.

.definition: from among (a number)
.example: In terms of colour, three out of five were silver.

.definition: a number of different types of things
.example: And a variety of issues seemed to stall the process.

.definition: to support or approve of something or someone
.example: I don’t know about you but I’m in favour.

.definition: to reach or arrive at a particular place
.example: If you get to the restaurant before us, just wait at the bar.

.definition: If you find yourself doing something, you are doing it without deciding or intending to do it.
.example: I find myself driving home.

.definition: return to the past
.example: If I could I’d go back and do it all over again.

.definition: immediately, at the same time
.example: I fell asleep at once

.definition: everything that is required
.example: She has what it takes to do the job

.definition: actually, in fact, used for talking about what really happens as opposed to what you think will or should happen
.example: Drivers say we need speed limits but, in practice, they don’t respect them.

.definition: a large number or amount of (things, people, etc.)
.example: Lots of them do travel during the winter months.

.definition: generally thought that
.example: The priest was said to be missing.

.definition: used to convey that an action, process, or situation is the result or product of a previous one.
.example: The supermarket in turn will donate seven thousand.

.definition: because, according to
.example: She came on the basis that it would help her.
